# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opencv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Usually, the camera parameters are represented in a 3 × 4 projection matrix called the *camera matrix*.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The **extrinsic parameters** define the camera *pose* (position and orientation) while the **intrinsic parameters** specify the camera image format (focal length, pixel size, and image origin).
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] This process is often called **geometric camera calibration** or simply **camera calibration**, although that term may also refer to photometric camera calibration or be restricted for the estimation of the intrinsic parameters only.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] **Exterior orientation** and **interior orientation** refer to the determination of only the extrinsic and intrinsic parameters, respectively.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The classic camera calibration requires special objects in the scene, which is not required in *camera auto-calibration*.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Camera resectioning is often used in the application of stereo vision where the camera projection matrices of two cameras are used to calculate the 3D world coordinates of a point viewed by both cameras.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The camera projection matrix is derived from the intrinsic and extrinsic parameters of the camera, and is often represented by the series of transformations; e.g., a matrix of camera intrinsic parameters, a 3 × 3 rotation matrix, and a translation vector.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The camera projection matrix can be used to associate points in a camera's image space with locations in 3D world space.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] In this context, we use $[u\ v\ 1]^{T}$ to represent a 2D point position in *pixel* coordinates and $[x_{w}\ y_{w}\ z_{w}\ 1]^{T}$ is used to represent a 3D point position in *world* coordinates.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] In both cases, they are represented in homogeneous coordinates (i.e. they have an additional last component, which is initially, by convention, a 1), which is the most common notation in robotics and rigid body transforms.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Referring to the pinhole camera model, a camera matrix M is used to denote a projective mapping from *world* coordinates to *pixel* coordinates.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] By dividing the matrix product by w , the theoretical value for the pixel coordinates can be found.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The K contains 5 intrinsic parameters of the specific camera model.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] These parameters encompass focal length, image sensor format, and camera principal point.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Nonlinear intrinsic parameters such as lens distortion are also important although they cannot be included in the linear camera model described by the intrinsic parameter matrix.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Many modern camera calibration algorithms estimate these intrinsic parameters as well in the form of non-linear optimisation techniques.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] This is done in the form of optimising the camera and distortion parameters in the form of what is generally known as bundle adjustment.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] $R,T$ are the **extrinsic parameters** which denote the coordinate system transformations from 3D world coordinates to 3D camera coordinates.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Equivalently, the extrinsic parameters define the position of the camera center and the camera's heading in world coordinates.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] T is the position of the origin of the world coordinate system expressed in coordinates of the camera-centered coordinate system.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] T is often mistakenly considered the position of the camera.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The position, C , of the camera expressed in world coordinates is $C=-R^{-1}T=-R^{T}T$ (since R is a rotation matrix).
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] This can be verified by checking that the point $[-R^{-1}T,1]$ is transformed to $[0,0,0,1]^{T}$ , which is what is expected (since the camera's location is, in the camera's coordinates, the origin).
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Camera calibration is often used as an early stage in computer vision.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] When a camera is used, light from the environment is focused on an image plane and captured.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] This process reduces the dimensions of the data taken in by the camera from three to two (light from a 3D scene is stored on a 2D image).
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Each pixel on the image plane therefore corresponds to a shaft of light from the original scene.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] There are many different approaches to calculate the intrinsic and extrinsic parameters for a specific camera setup.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Zhang's method is a camera calibration method that uses traditional calibration techniques (known calibration points) and self-calibration techniques (correspondence between the calibration points when they are in different positions).
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] To perform a full calibration by the Zhang method, at least three different images of the calibration target/gauge are required, either by moving the gauge or the camera itself.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] If some of the intrinsic parameters are given as data (orthogonality of the image or optical center coordinates), the number of images required can be reduced to two.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] In a first step, an approximation of the estimated projection matrix H between the calibration target and the image plane is determined using DLT method.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Subsequently, self-calibration techniques are applied to obtain the image of the absolute conic matrix.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The main contribution of Zhang's method is how to, given n poses of the calibration target, extract a constrained intrinsic matrix K , along with n instances of R and T calibration parameters.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Assume we have a homography ${\textbf {H}}$ that maps points $x_{\pi }$ on a "probe plane" $\pi$ to points x on the image.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The circular points $I,J={\begin{bmatrix}1&\pm j&0\end{bmatrix}}^{\mathrm {T} }$ lie on both our probe plane $\pi$ and on the absolute conic $\Omega _{\infty }$ .
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Lying on $\Omega _{\infty }$ of course means they are also projected onto the *image* of the absolute conic (IAC) $\omega$ , thus $x_{1}^{T}\omega x_{1}=0$ and $x_{2}^{T}\omega x_{2}=0$ .
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Tsai's algorithm, a significant method in camera calibration, involves several detailed steps for accurately determining a camera's orientation and position in 3D space.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The process begins with the **initial calibration** stage, where a series of images are captured by the camera.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] These images, often featuring a known calibration pattern like a checkerboard, are used to estimate intrinsic camera parameters such as focal length and optical center.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] In some applications, variants of the chessboard target are used which are robust to partial occlusions.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Such targets like the ChArUco and PuzzleBoard targets simplify the measurement of distortions in the corners of the camera sensor.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Following initial calibration, the algorithm undertakes **pose estimation**.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] This involves calculating the camera's position and orientation relative to a known object in the scene.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The process typically requires identifying specific points in the calibration pattern and solving for the camera's rotation and translation vectors.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] The final phase is the **refinement of parameters**.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] In this stage, the algorithm refines the lens distortion coefficients, addressing radial and tangential distortions.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Further optimization of internal and external camera parameters is performed to enhance the calibration accuracy.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] This structured approach has positioned Tsai's Algorithm as a pivotal technique in both academic research and practical applications within robotics and industrial metrology.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Selby's camera calibration method addresses the auto-calibration of X-ray camera systems.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] X-ray camera systems, consisting of the X-ray generating tube and a solid state detector can be modelled as pinhole camera systems, comprising 9 intrinsic and extrinsic camera parameters.
[src:opencv/camera-resectioning] Intensity based registration based on an arbitrary X-ray image and a reference model (as a tomographic dataset) can then be used to determine the relative camera parameters without the need of a special calibration body or any ground-truth data.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:opencv/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:opencv/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:opencv/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:opencv/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The purpose of early image processing was to improve the quality of the image.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] In image processing, the input is a low-quality image, and the output is an image with improved quality.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Common image processing includes image enhancement, restoration, encoding, and compression.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The first successful application was the American Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL).
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] They used image processing techniques such as geometric correction, gradation transformation, noise removal, etc. on the thousands of lunar photos sent back by the Space Detector Ranger 7 in 1964, taking into account the position of the Sun and the environment of the Moon.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The impact of the successful mapping of the Moon's surface map by the computer has been a success.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Later, more complex image processing was performed on the nearly 100,000 photos sent back by the spacecraft, so that the topographic map, color map and panoramic mosaic of the Moon were obtained, which achieved extraordinary results and laid a solid foundation for human landing on the Moon.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The cost of processing was fairly high, however, with the computing equipment of that era.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] That changed in the 1970s, when digital image processing proliferated as cheaper computers and dedicated hardware became available.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] This led to images being processed in real-time, for some dedicated problems such as television standards conversion.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] As general-purpose computers became faster, they started to take over the role of dedicated hardware for all but the most specialized and computer-intensive operations.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] With the fast computers and signal processors available in the 2000s, digital image processing has become the most common form of image processing, and is generally used because it is not only the most versatile method, but also the cheapest.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The basis for modern image sensors is metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, This led to the development of digital semiconductor image sensors, including the charge-coupled device (CCD) and later the CMOS sensor.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The charge-coupled device was invented by Willard S.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] While researching MOS technology, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The CCD is a semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The NMOS active-pixel sensor (APS) was invented by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] This was enabled by advances in MOS semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The NMOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) was later developed by Eric Fossum's team at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] By 2007, sales of CMOS sensors had surpassed CCD sensors.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] MOS image sensors are widely used in optical mouse technology.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The first optical mouse, invented by Richard F.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Lyon at Xerox in 1980, used a 5 μm NMOS integrated circuit sensor chip.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Since the first commercial optical mouse, the IntelliMouse introduced in 1999, most optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] An important development in digital image compression technology was the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a lossy compression technique first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] DCT compression became the basis for JPEG, which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group in 1992.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] JPEG compresses images down to much smaller file sizes, and has become the most widely used image file format on the Internet.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Its highly efficient DCT compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos, with several billion JPEG images produced every day as of 2015.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Medical imaging techniques produce very large amounts of data, especially from CT, MRI and PET modalities.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] As a result, storage and communications of electronic image data are prohibitive without the use of compression.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] JPEG 2000 image compression is used by the DICOM standard for storage and transmission of medical images.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The cost and feasibility of accessing large image data sets over low or various bandwidths are further addressed by use of another DICOM standard, called JPIP, to enable efficient streaming of the JPEG 2000 compressed image data.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Electronic signal processing was revolutionized by the wide adoption of MOS technology in the 1970s.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] MOS integrated circuit technology was the basis for the first single-chip microprocessors and microcontrollers in the early 1970s, and then the first single-chip digital signal processor (DSP) chips in the late 1970s.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] DSP chips have since been widely used in digital image processing.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) image compression algorithm has been widely implemented in DSP chips, with many companies developing DSP chips based on DCT technology.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] DCTs are widely used for encoding, decoding, video coding, audio coding, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, analog-to-digital conversion, formatting luminance and color differences, and color formats such as YUV444 and YUV411.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Digital image processing allows the use of much more complex algorithms, and hence, can offer both more sophisticated performance at simple tasks, and the implementation of methods which would be impossible by analogue means.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Digital filters are used to blur and sharpen digital images.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Notice that the highpass filter shows extra edges when zero padded compared to the repeated edge padding.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] MATLAB example for spatial domain highpass filtering.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] To apply the affine matrix to an image, the image is converted to a matrix in which each entry corresponds to the pixel intensity at that location.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Then each pixel's location can be represented as a vector indicating the coordinates of that pixel in the image, [*x*, *y*], where *x* and *y* are the row and column of a pixel in the image matrix.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate to be multiplied by an affine-transformation matrix, which gives the position that the pixel value will be copied to in the output image.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] However, to allow transformations that require translation transformations, 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates are needed.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The third dimension is usually set to a non-zero constant, usually 1, so that the new coordinate is [*x*, *y*, 1].
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate vector to be multiplied by a 3×3 matrix, enabling translation shifts.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Thus, the third dimension, i.e., the constant 1, allows translation.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Because matrix multiplication is associative, multiple affine transformations can be combined into a single affine transformation by multiplying the matrix of each individual transformation in the order that the transformations are done.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] This results in a single matrix that, when applied to a point vector, gives the same result as all the individual transformations performed on the vector [*x*, *y*, 1] in sequence.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Thus, a sequence of affine transformation matrices can be reduced to a single affine transformation matrix.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] For example, 2-dimensional coordinates only permit rotation about the origin (0, 0).
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] But 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates can be used to first translate any point to (0, 0), then perform the rotation, and lastly translate the origin (0, 0) back to the original point (the opposite of the first translation).
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] These three affine transformations can be combined into a single matrix, thus allowing rotation around any point in the image.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Mathematical morphology (MM) is a nonlinear image processing framework that analyzes shapes within images by probing local pixel neighborhoods using a small, predefined function called a structuring element.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] In the context of grayscale images, MM is especially useful for denoising through dilation and erosion—primitive operators that can be combined to build more complex filters.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Here, ${\mathcal {S}}$ defines the neighborhood of relative coordinates $(m,n)$ over which local operations are computed.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The values of $B(m,n)$ bias the image during dilation and erosion.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] MM operations, such as opening and closing, are composite processes that utilize both dilation and erosion to modify the structure of an image.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] These operations are particularly useful for tasks such as noise removal, shape smoothing, and object separation.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] For example, applying opening to an image f with a structuring element B would first reduce small details (through erosion) and then restore the main shapes (through dilation).
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] This ensures that unwanted noise is removed without significantly altering the size or shape of larger objects.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] For instance, applying closing to the same image f would fill in small gaps within objects, such as connecting breaks in thin lines or closing small holes, while ensuring that the surrounding areas are not significantly affected.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Both opening and closing can be visualized as ways of refining the structure of an image: opening simplifies and removes small, unnecessary details, while closing consolidates and connects objects to form more cohesive structures.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Digital cameras generally include specialized digital image processing hardware – either dedicated chips or added circuitry on other chips – to convert the raw data from their image sensor into a color-corrected image in a standard image file format.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Additional post-processing techniques increase edge sharpness or color saturation to create more naturally looking images.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Face detection can be implemented with mathematical morphology, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), and horizontal projection.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The feature-based method of face detection uses skin tone, edge detection, face shape, and features of a face (like eyes, mouth, etc.) to achieve face detection.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The skin tone, face shape, and all the unique elements that only the human face has can be described as features.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Normally, HSV or RGB color spaces are suitable for the skin filter.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] After filtering images with skin tone, to get the face edge, morphology and DCT are used to remove noise and fill up missing skin areas.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] DCT is to avoid the object with skin-like tone.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Since human faces always have higher texture.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Sobel operator or other operators can be applied to detect face edge.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] To position human features like eyes, using the projection and finding the peak of the histogram of projection helps to get the detailed features like mouth, hair, and lip.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Image quality can be influenced by camera vibration, over-exposure, gray level distribution too centralized, and noise, etc.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] For example, the noise problem can be solved by smoothing method, while the gray level distribution problem can be improved by histogram equalization.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] In drawing, if there is some dissatisfied color, taking some color around the dissatisfied color and averaging them.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The smoothing method can be implemented with a mask and convolution.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Take the small image and mask, for instance, as below.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] The original image pixel is 1, 4, 28, 30.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] After the smoothing mask, the pixel becomes 9, 10, 9, 9, respectively.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Generally, given a gray level histogram from an image as below.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Changing the histogram to a uniform distribution from an image is usually what we call histogram equalization.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] In discrete time, the area of gray level histogram is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}H(p_{i})$ (see figure 1) while the area of uniform distribution is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}G(q_{i})$ (see figure 2).
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] Moreover, based on the definition of a function, the Gray level histogram method is like finding a function f that satisfies f(p)=q.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] **Variability in image quality**: Variations in image quality and resolution, including blurry images and incomplete details, can hinder uniform processing across a database.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] **Object detection and Recognition**: Identifying and recognising objects within images, especially in complex scenarios with multiple objects and occlusions, poses a significant challenge.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] **Data annotation and labelling**: Labelling diverse and multiple images for machine recognition is crucial for further processing accuracy, as incorrect identification can lead to unrealistic results.
[src:opencv/digital-image-processing] **Computational resource intensity**: Accessing adequate computational resources for image processing can be challenging and costly, hindering progress without sufficient resources.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In computer vision and image processing, a **feature** is a piece of information about the content of an image; typically about whether a certain region of the image has certain properties.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Features may be specific structures in the image such as points, edges or objects.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Features may also be the result of a general neighborhood operation or **feature detection** applied to the image.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Other examples of features are related to motion in image sequences, or to shapes defined in terms of curves or boundaries between different image regions.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] More broadly a *feature* is any piece of information that is relevant for solving the computational task related to a certain application.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] This is the same sense as feature in machine learning and pattern recognition generally, though image processing has a very sophisticated collection of features.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The feature concept is very general and the choice of features in a particular computer vision system may be highly dependent on the specific problem at hand.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] There is no universal or exact definition of what constitutes a feature, and the exact definition often depends on the problem or the type of application.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, a feature is typically defined as an "interesting" part of an image, and features are used as a starting point for many computer vision algorithms.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Since features are used as the starting point and main primitives for subsequent algorithms, the overall algorithm will often only be as good as its feature detector.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consequently, the desirable property for a feature detector is *repeatability*: whether or not the same feature will be detected in two or more different images of the same scene.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Feature detection is a low-level image processing operation.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] That is, it is usually performed as the first operation on an image and examines every pixel to see if there is a feature present at that pixel.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] If this is part of a larger algorithm, then the algorithm will typically only examine the image in the region of the features.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] As a built-in pre-requisite to feature detection, the input image is usually smoothed by a Gaussian kernel in a scale-space representation and one or several feature images are computed, often expressed in terms of local image derivative operations.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Occasionally, when feature detection is computationally expensive and there are time constraints, a higher-level algorithm may be used to guide the feature detection stage so that only certain parts of the image are searched for features.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] There are many computer vision algorithms that use feature detection as the initial step, so as a result, a very large number of feature detectors have been developed.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] These vary widely in the kinds of feature detected, the computational complexity and the repeatability.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The distinction becomes relevant when the resulting detected features are relatively sparse.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Although local decisions are made, the output from a feature detection step does not need to be a binary image.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The result is often represented in terms of sets of (connected or unconnected) coordinates of the image points where features have been detected, sometimes with subpixel accuracy.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] When feature extraction is done without local decision making, the result is often referred to as a *feature image*.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consequently, a feature image can be seen as an image in the sense that it is a function of the same spatial (or temporal) variables as the original image, but where the pixel values hold information about image features instead of intensity or color.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] This means that a feature image can be processed in a similar way as an ordinary image generated by an image sensor.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Feature images are also often computed as integrated step in algorithms for feature detection.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In some applications, it is not sufficient to extract only one type of feature to obtain the relevant information from the image data.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Instead, two or more different features are extracted, resulting in two or more feature descriptors at each image point.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] A common practice is to organize the information provided by all these descriptors as the elements of one single vector, commonly referred to as a **feature vector**.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The set of all possible feature vectors constitutes a **feature space**.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] A common example of feature vectors appears when each image point is to be classified as belonging to a specific class.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Assuming that each image point has a corresponding feature vector based on a suitable set of features, meaning that each class is well separated in the corresponding feature space, the classification of each image point can be done using standard classification method.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] , which are correlated with "nodes" that represent visual features.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two features.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Another and related example occurs when neural network-based processing is applied to images.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The input data fed to the neural network is often given in terms of a feature vector from each image point, where the vector is constructed from several different features extracted from the image data.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] During a learning phase, the network can itself find which combinations of different features are useful for solving the problem at hand.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Edges are points where there is a boundary (or an edge) between two image regions.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In general, an edge can be of almost arbitrary shape, and may include junctions.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In practice, edges are usually defined as sets of points in the image that have a strong gradient magnitude.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Furthermore, some common algorithms will then chain high gradient points together to form a more complete description of an edge.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] These algorithms usually place some constraints on the properties of an edge, such as shape, smoothness, and gradient value.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Locally, edges have a one-dimensional structure.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The terms corners and interest points are used somewhat interchangeably and refer to point-like features in an image, which have a local two-dimensional structure.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The name "Corner" arose since early algorithms first performed edge detection, and then analyzed the edges to find rapid changes in direction (corners).
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] These algorithms were then developed so that explicit edge detection was no longer required, for instance by looking for high levels of curvature in the image gradient.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] It was then noticed that the so-called corners were also being detected on parts of the image that were not corners in the traditional sense (for instance a small bright spot on a dark background may be detected).
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] These points are frequently known as interest points, but the term "corner" is used by tradition.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Blobs provide a complementary description of image structures in terms of regions, as opposed to corners that are more point-like.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, blob descriptors may often contain a preferred point (a local maximum of an operator response or a center of gravity) which means that many blob detectors may also be regarded as interest point operators.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Blob detectors can detect areas in an image that are too smooth to be detected by a corner detector.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consider shrinking an image and then performing corner detection.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The detector will respond to points that are sharp in the shrunk image, but may be smooth in the original image.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] It is at this point that the difference between a corner detector and a blob detector becomes somewhat vague.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] To a large extent, this distinction can be remedied by including an appropriate notion of scale.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, due to their response properties to different types of image structures at different scales, the LoG and DoH blob detectors are also mentioned in the article on corner detection.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] For elongated objects, the notion of *ridges* is a natural tool.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] A ridge descriptor computed from a grey-level image can be seen as a generalization of a medial axis.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] From a practical viewpoint, a ridge can be thought of as a one-dimensional curve that represents an axis of symmetry, and in addition has an attribute of local ridge width associated with each ridge point.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Unfortunately, however, it is algorithmically harder to extract ridge features from general classes of grey-level images than edge-, corner- or blob features.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, ridge descriptors are frequently used for road extraction in aerial images and for extracting blood vessels in medical images—see ridge detection.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The extraction of features are sometimes made over several scalings.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] One of these methods is the scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT).
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Once features have been detected, a local image patch around the feature can be extracted.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] This extraction may involve quite considerable amounts of image processing.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The result is known as a feature descriptor or feature vector.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Among the approaches that are used to feature description, one can mention *N*-jets and local histograms (see scale-invariant feature transform for one example of a local histogram descriptor).
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In addition to such attribute information, the feature detection step by itself may also provide complementary attributes, such as the edge orientation and gradient magnitude in edge detection and the polarity and the strength of the blob in blob detection.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] A specific image feature, defined in terms of a specific structure in the image data, can often be represented in different ways.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] For example, an edge can be represented as a Boolean variable in each image point that describes whether an edge is present at that point.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Alternatively, we can instead use a representation that provides a certainty measure instead of a Boolean statement of the edge's existence and combine this with information about the orientation of the edge.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Similarly, the color of a specific region can either be represented in terms of the average color (three scalars) or a color histogram (three functions).
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] When a computer vision system or computer vision algorithm is designed the choice of feature representation can be a critical issue.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In some cases, a higher level of detail in the description of a feature may be necessary for solving the problem, but this comes at the cost of having to deal with more data and more demanding processing.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Below, some of the factors which are relevant for choosing a suitable representation are discussed.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In this discussion, an instance of a feature representation is referred to as a *feature descriptor*, or simply *descriptor*.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Two examples of image features are local edge orientation and local velocity in an image sequence.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In the case of orientation, the value of this feature may be more or less undefined if more than one edge are present in the corresponding neighborhood.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Local velocity is undefined if the corresponding image region does not contain any spatial variation.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] As a consequence of this observation, it may be relevant to use a feature representation that includes a measure of certainty or confidence related to the statement about the feature value.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Otherwise, it is a typical situation that the same descriptor is used to represent feature values of low certainty and feature values close to zero, with a resulting ambiguity in the interpretation of this descriptor.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Depending on the application, such an ambiguity may or may not be acceptable.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In particular, if a featured image will be used in subsequent processing, it may be a good idea to employ a feature representation that includes information about certainty or confidence.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] This enables a new feature descriptor to be computed from several descriptors, for example, computed at the same image point but at different scales, or from different but neighboring points, in terms of a weighted average where the weights are derived from the corresponding certainties.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In the simplest case, the corresponding computation can be implemented as a low-pass filtering of the featured image.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The resulting feature image will, in general, be more stable to noise.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] In addition to having certainty measures included in the representation, the representation of the corresponding feature values may itself be suitable for an averaging operation or not.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Most feature representations can be averaged in practice, but only in certain cases can the resulting descriptor be given a correct interpretation in terms of a feature value.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Such representations are referred to as *averageable*.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] For example, if the orientation of an edge is represented in terms of an angle, this representation must have a discontinuity where the angle wraps from its maximal value to its minimal value.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consequently, it can happen that two similar orientations are represented by angles that have a mean that does not lie close to either of the original angles and, hence, this representation is not averageable.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] There are other representations of edge orientation, such as the structure tensor, which are averageable.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Another example relates to motion, where in some cases only the normal velocity relative to some edge can be extracted.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] If two such features have been extracted and they can be assumed to refer to same true velocity, this velocity is not given as the average of the normal velocity vectors.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Hence, normal velocity vectors are not averageable.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Instead, there are other representations of motions, using matrices or tensors, that give the true velocity in terms of an average operation of the normal velocity descriptors.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] Features detected in each image can be matched across multiple images to establish *corresponding features* such as *corresponding points*.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] The algorithm is based on comparing and analyzing point correspondences between the reference image and the target image.
[src:opencv/feature-detection-computer-vision] If any part of the cluttered scene shares correspondences greater than the threshold, that part of the cluttered scene image is targeted and considered to include the reference object there.
[src:opencv/opencv] Officially launched in 1999, the OpenCV project was initially an Intel Research initiative to advance CPU-intensive applications, part of a series of projects including real-time ray tracing and 3D display walls.
[src:opencv/opencv] The main contributors to the project included a number of optimization experts in Intel Russia, as well as Intel's Performance Library Team.
[src:opencv/opencv] The first alpha version of OpenCV was released to the public at the IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition in 2000, and five betas were released between 2001 and 2005.
[src:opencv/opencv] The first 1.0 version was released in 2006.
[src:opencv/opencv] A version 1.1 "pre-release" was released in October 2008.
[src:opencv/opencv] The second major release of the OpenCV was in October 2009.
[src:opencv/opencv] OpenCV 2 includes major changes to the C++ interface, aiming at easier, more type-safe patterns, new functions, and better implementations for existing ones in terms of performance (especially on multi-core systems).
[src:opencv/opencv] Official releases now occur every six months and development is now done by an independent Russian team supported by commercial corporations.
[src:opencv/opencv] In August 2012, support for OpenCV was taken over by a non-profit foundation, OpenCV.org, which maintains a developer and user site.
[src:opencv/opencv] In May 2016, Intel signed an agreement to acquire Itseez, a leading developer of OpenCV.
[src:opencv/opencv] OpenCV is written in the programming language C++, as is its primary interface.
[src:opencv/opencv] There are language bindings in Python, Java, and MATLAB/Octave.
[src:opencv/opencv] The application programming interface (API) for these interfaces can be found in the online documentation.
[src:opencv/opencv] Wrapper libraries in several languages have been developed to encourage adoption by a wider audience.
[src:opencv/opencv] In version 3.4, JavaScript bindings for a selected subset of OpenCV functions were released as OpenCV.js, to be used for web platforms.
[src:opencv/opencv] If the library finds Intel's Integrated Performance Primitives on the system, it will use these proprietary optimized routines to accelerate itself.
[src:opencv/opencv] A Compute Unified Device Architecture (CUDA) based graphics processing unit (GPU) interface has been in progress since September 2010.
[src:opencv/opencv] An OpenCL-based GPU interface has been in progress since October 2012, documentation for version 2.4.13.3 can be found at docs.opencv.org.
[src:opencv/opencv] An IPU may also utilise OpenCV hardware acceleration.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] The concept of optic flow has roots as far back as Euclid's *Optics*, but its modern formulation arose from Second World War research into pilot vision during landing.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Several researchers arrived at the idea independently; James J.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Gibson gave it its most influential treatment, publishing his theory in 1947 and created the term "optic flow" in 1950.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Optical flow can be estimated in a number of ways.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Many classical models use the intuitive assumption of *brightness constancy*; that even if a point moves between frames, its brightness stays constant.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] To formalise this intuitive assumption, consider two consecutive frames from a video sequence, with intensity $I(x,y,t)$ , where $(x,y)$ refer to pixel coordinates and t refers to time.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] where $\mathbf {w$ is the displacement vector between a point in the first frame and the corresponding point in the second frame.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] By itself, the brightness constancy constraint cannot be solved for u and v at each pixel, since there is only one equation and two unknowns.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This is known as the *aperture problem*.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Therefore, additional constraints must be imposed to estimate the flow field.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Perhaps the most natural approach to addressing the aperture problem is to apply a smoothness constraint or a *regularization constraint* to the flow field.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] where $\Omega$ is the extent of the images $I(x,y)$ , $\nabla$ is the gradient operator, $\alpha$ is a constant, and $\Psi ()$ is a loss function.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This optimisation problem is difficult to solve owing to its non-linearity.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] To address this issue, one can use a *variational approach* and linearise the brightness constancy constraint using a first order Taylor series approximation.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] For convenience, the derivatives of the image, ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial x}}$ , ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial y}}$ and ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial t}}$ are often condensed to become $I_{x}$ , $I_{y}$ and $I_{t}$ .
[src:opencv/optical-flow] For the choice of $\Psi (x)=x^{2}$ , this method is the same as the Horn-Schunck method.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Of course, other choices of cost function have been used such as $\Psi (x)={\sqrt {x^{2}+\epsilon ^{2}}}$ , which is a differentiable variant of the $L^{1}$ norm.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] To solve the aforementioned optimization problem, one can use the Euler-Lagrange equations to provide a system of partial differential equations for each point in $I(x,y,t)$ .
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Since the image data is made up of discrete pixels, these equations are discretised.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Doing so yields a system of linear equations which can be solved for $(u,v)$ at each pixel, using an iterative scheme such as Gauss-Seidel.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Although, linearising the brightness constancy constraint simplifies the optimisation problem significantly, the linearisation is only valid for small displacements and/or smooth images.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] To avoid this problem, a multi-scale or coarse-to-fine approach is often used.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] In such a scheme, the images are initially downsampled and the linearised Euler-Lagrange equations are solved at the reduced resolution.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] The estimated flow field at this scale is then used to initialise the process at next scale.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This initialisation process is often performed by warping one frame using the current estimate of flow field so that it is as similar to other as possible.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] An alternate approach is to discretize the optimisation problem and then perform a search of the possible $(u,v)$ values without linearising it.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This search is often performed using Max-flow min-cut theorem algorithms, linear programming or belief propagation methods.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] These regularized methods typically require manual tuning of the Lagrange multiplier, the so-called regularization parameters.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] There has been some progress in the automatic determination of these parameters in the context of optical flow applied to particle image velocimetry (PIV) data.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Instead of applying the regularization constraint on a point by point basis as per a regularized model, one can group pixels into regions and estimate the motion of these regions.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This is known as a *parametric model*, since the motion of these regions is parameterized.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] In formulating optical flow estimation in this way, one makes the assumption that the motion field in each region be fully characterised by a set of parameters.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] The simplest parametric model is the Lucas-Kanade method.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This uses rectangular regions and parameterises the motion as purely translational.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] The Lucas-Kanade method uses the original brightness constancy constraint as the data cost term and selects $g(x,y)=1$ .
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Other possible local loss functions include the negative normalized cross-correlation between the two frames.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Instead of seeking to model optical flow directly, one can train a machine learning system to estimate optical flow.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Since 2015, when FlowNet was proposed, learning based models have been applied to optical flow and have gained prominence.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] However, with the advent of transformer architecture in 2017, transformer based models have gained prominence.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] A significant shift occurred with the introduction of RAFT (Recurrent All-Pairs Field Transforms), which replaced coarse-to-fine pyramids with a single GRU-based state that iteratively updates the flow field.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] By maintaining a constant feature resolution at 1/8 of the input, RAFT significantly improved the preservation of fine details and robustness to fast motion compared to previous bottleneck-heavy designs, influencing a wide range of subsequent models that adopt similar iterative update mechanisms.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] However, the all-pairs correlation used in such models is computationally expensive; for high-resolution content like FullHD or 4K, global matching can require more than 32 GB of VRAM, making it impractical for consumer-grade GPUs.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] To address this, efficiency-focused methods such as Flow1D, MeFlow, and Memfof have been developed.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] While these approaches generally optimize memory usage by decomposing the 2D search space, the latter optimizes correlation volumes for high-resolution multi-frame sequences, providing a practical implementation for standard GPUs.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Most learning-based approaches to optical flow use supervised learning.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] In this case, many frame pairs of video data and their corresponding ground-truth flow fields are used to optimise the parameters of the learning-based model to accurately estimate optical flow.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This process often relies on vast synthetic training datasets, such as FlyingChairs and FlyingThings3D, due to the number of parameters involved.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] The models are then evaluated on benchmarks like MPI Sintel, KITTI, and the high-resolution Spring dataset.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] However, models trained exclusively on synthetic data often struggle with the domain gap when applied to real-world footage.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] To address this, some learning-based optical flow approaches use self-supervised learning (sometimes called unsupervised learning) to reduce the need for large datasets with ground-truth data and leverage real-world footage without labels during training.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Instead of training models to minimise the differences between estimated and ground-truth flow fields, they are trained to achieve learning objectives such as brightness constancy and smoothness of the flow field.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] More recently, methods like CroCo have introduced cross-view completion pre-training.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Forcing the network to predict the masked regions of one image using the full second image teaches the model a strong geometric understanding and better generalization than models trained solely on task-specific labels.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Motion estimation and video compression have developed as a major aspect of optical flow research.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Optical flow was used by robotics researchers in many areas such as: object detection and tracking, image dominant plane extraction, movement detection, robot navigation and visual odometry.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Optical flow information has been recognized as being useful for controlling micro air vehicles.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] The application of optical flow includes the problem of inferring not only the motion of the observer and objects in the scene, but also the structure of objects and the environment.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Since awareness of motion and the generation of mental maps of the structure of our environment are critical components of animal (and human) vision, the conversion of this innate ability to a computer capability is similarly crucial in the field of machine vision.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Consider a five-frame clip of a ball moving from the bottom left of a field of vision, to the top right.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Motion estimation techniques can determine that on a two dimensional plane the ball is moving up and to the right and vectors describing this motion can be extracted from the sequence of frames.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] For the purposes of video compression (e.g., MPEG), the sequence is now described as well as it needs to be.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] However, in the field of machine vision, the question of whether the ball is moving to the right or if the observer is moving to the left is unknowable yet critical information.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Not even if a static, patterned background were present in the five frames, could we confidently state that the ball was moving to the right, because the pattern might have an infinite distance to the observer.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Optical flow has also been applied to fluid mechanics as a method of estimating flow patterns in a non-invasive way if visible tracer particles are added.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] This approach is called particle image velocimetry (PIV).
[src:opencv/optical-flow] It has been shown that optical flow methods can provide higher accuracy than traditional cross-correlation in PIV processing .
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Various configurations of optical flow sensors exist.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] One configuration is an image sensor chip connected to a processor programmed to run an optical flow algorithm.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Another configuration uses a vision chip, which is an integrated circuit having both the image sensor and the processor on the same die, allowing for a compact implementation.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] An example of this is a generic optical mouse sensor used in an optical mouse.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] In some cases the processing circuitry may be implemented using analog or mixed-signal circuits to enable fast optical flow computation using minimal current consumption.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] One area of contemporary research is the use of neuromorphic engineering techniques to implement circuits that respond to optical flow, and thus may be appropriate for use in an optical flow sensor.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Such circuits may draw inspiration from biological neural circuitry that similarly responds to optical flow.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are used extensively in computer optical mice, as the main sensing component for measuring the motion of the mouse across a surface.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are also being used in robotics applications, primarily where there is a need to measure visual motion or relative motion between the robot and other objects in the vicinity of the robot.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] The use of optical flow sensors in unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs), for stability and obstacle avoidance, is also an area of current research.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] As early as Euclid's *Optics* note was made of the geometry underlying optic flow.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Helmholtz's nineteenth-century account of motion parallax also implicitly concerns it.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] However, its explicit identification arose during the Second World War due the need to understand how pilots judge height and direction during landing.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] MacCurdy, in advise to the Royal Air Force in the late 1920s, had earlier observed that during a straight descent the point on the ground being approached stays fixed in the pilot's visual field while all other points appear to stream away from it.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Grindley, in a classified 1942 report then mathematically analyzed how retinal velocity changed during self-motion to enable an individual to accurately estimate visual speed.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] He, however, considered only this as a cue to altitude and not information to determine travel.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Army Air Forces, first identified that retinal velocities radiate from a "focus of expansion" in the direction of travel.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Moreover, that eye movements do not disturb this, and that it was the global pattern—not individual velocities—that provided this information.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] In 1947, he published the theory, and in 1950 gave the phenomenon the name "optic flow".
[src:opencv/optical-flow] In 1955, he together with Paul Olum and Frank Rosenblatt detailed its mathematics.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Calvert at the Royal Aircraft Establishment came to a similar ideas when researching on airport approach lighting.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] In 1949, he proposed them as the "parafoveal streamer theory" which described how pilots use the pattern and speed of visual streamers to control their descent.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Gibson stressed the importance of optic flow for affordance perception, the ability to discern possibilities for action within the environment.
[src:opencv/optical-flow] Followers of Gibson and his ecological approach to psychology have further demonstrated the role of the optical flow stimulus for the perception of movement by the observer in the world; perception of the shape, distance and movement of objects in the world; and the control of locomotion.
